The Warburg Effect and Cancer Cell Metabolism
The Warburg effect observes that cancer cells prefer glucose as their primary source of energy, and they behave differently from normal cells, which prefer oxidative phosphorylation to make energy 00:02:21
There are two ways that a cell can make energy: glycolysis, which does not require oxygen, and oxidative phosphorylation, which requires oxygen and is the primary method used by normal, healthy body cells 00:03:12
Cancer cells rely primarily on glycolysis, even when oxygen is present, and they favor glycolysis over oxidative phosphorylation, which is why understanding the Warburg effect is crucial in finding ways to starve cancer cells 00:04:34
Glucose can be used by both normal and cancer cells, but fat can only be burned in the presence of oxygen through oxidative phosphorylation, making it a less preferred fuel source for cancer cells 00:04:06
